[[ファイル:Nakashima-Jinjya Torii001.jpg|thumb|250px|Torii and approach]]

'''Nakashima Shrine''' (なかしまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Toyooka|Q696388|qid=Q696388|1=Toyooka, Hyōgo}}, {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|qid=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}<ref name="mainichi-np-2014-4-20" />. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank was prefectural shrine. Revered by confectionery makers as the "progenitor deity of sweets"<ref name="mainichi-np-2014-4-20" />, it has branch shrines across Japan.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The principal deity is {{ill|lt=Tajimamori|Q11316133|qid=Q11316133|lt=Tajimamori-no-Mikoto|1=Tajimamori}}<ref name="mainichi-np-2014-4-20" />, with {{ill|lt=Amenoyukawatano-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN|lt=Amenoyukawatano-no-Kami}} as associated deity.

Tajimamori-no-Mikoto is said to be a fifth-generation descendant of Amenohiboko and, by order of {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|qid=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}} recorded in the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}', brought back from {{ill|lt=Tokoyo no Kuni|Q11060259|qid=Q11060259|1=Tokoyo no kuni}} the "Tokijiku no Kagu no Mi" (the {{ill|lt=tachibana|Q11121938|qid=Q11121938|lt=tachibana|1=Tachibana orange}} citrus)<ref>Suinin chronicle, postscript section, 3rd month day 12 (corresponding to {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|qid=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}} year 2).</ref>. Because tachibana (prototype of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=mikan|1=UNKNOWN}} and other {{ill|lt=citrus fruits|Q3216053|qid=Q3216053|1=Citreae}}) was regarded as a top-class confection ingredient, he is revered as deity of confectionery and citrus ancestor deity<ref>{{Cite web|和書|title=Yoroku: "Tokoyo no Kuni" and ancient Japanese...|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20171227/ddm/001/070/112000c|website=Mainichi Shimbun|accessdate=2021-11-25|language=ja}}</ref>. He is also regarded as a sericulture deity because he is said to have settled at the present site, reclaimed the land, and encouraged {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=sericulture|1=UNKNOWN}}.

Amenoyukawatano-no-Kami was deity of Ami Shrine, merged in the medieval period, and is ancestral deity of the Toritori no Muraji clan. According to the Nihon Shoki, he captured a swan for prince {{ill|lt=Homutsuwake-no-Mikoto|Q11631423|qid=Q11631423|1=Homutsuwake no Mikoto}} by imperial order<ref>Suinin chronicle, year 23 entry.</ref>. One theory says he was enshrined near Wananami no Minato, where the swan was captured in the {{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|qid=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}<ref>However, the Kojiki does not name Amenoyukawatano-no-Kami; it says the swan was captured by Yamanobe no Ōtaka (Suinin record).</ref>.

=== History ===
According to '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kokushi Monjo|1=UNKNOWN}}'<ref>"Kokushi Monjo" is said to have been compiled in {{ill|lt=Ten'en|Q1327245|qid=Q1327245|1=Ten'en}} 3 (975) by a person called Yōkō Mashika, and is treated as doubtful, though some see old traditions in it (Keiichi Imai, 'Amenohiboko,' Sōgeisha, 1966). See also "{{ill|lt=Koshi Koden|Q11410976|qid=Q11410976|1=koshi koden}}".</ref>, in {{ill|lt=Empress Suiko|Q298057|qid=Q298057|1=Empress Suiko}} 15 ({{ill|lt=606|Q31043|qid=Q31043|1=606}}), Miyake no Kishi, a seventh-generation descendant of Tajimamori, began enshrining Tajimamori as ancestral deity. The name "Nakashima" is explained by saying Tajimamori's tomb appears like an island in the pond of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Emperor Suinin's mausoleum|1=UNKNOWN}}. In the medieval period, four shrines in Ami-gō (Ariko Shrine, Amuka Shrine, Ami Shrine, and Kasumi Shrine) were merged and it was called "Gosha Daimyōjin," but later all except Ami Shrine (Amenoyukawatano-no-Kami) were separated.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}}) October it was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}; in year 28 ({{ill|lt=1895|Q7844|qid=Q7844|1=1895}}) December it became {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}, and in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 10 ({{ill|lt=1935|Q18658|qid=Q18658|1=1935}}) October it was promoted to prefectural shrine.

=== Festival ===
The {{ill|lt=annual festival|Q11385469|qid=Q11385469|1=Reisai}} is held on the third Sunday of April, also called the '''Confectionery Festival''' and '''Kikkasai''' (Tachibana Flower Festival). Many confectionery industry representatives from across Japan attend and pray for prosperity.

=== Shrine buildings ===
The honden is {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|qid=Q210684|lt=niken-sha nagare-zukuri|1=Nagare-zukuri}} with {{ill|lt=hiwadabuki|Q90373477|qid=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}} roofing. After a fire during the {{ill|lt=Ōei|Q1193078|qid=Q1193078|1=Ōei}} period ({{ill|lt=1394|Q6398|qid=Q6398|1=1394}}-{{ill|lt=1428|Q6315|qid=Q6315|1=1428}}), it was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Shōchō|Q1193070|qid=Q1193070|1=Shōchō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1428|Q6315|qid=Q6315|1=1428}}). It is designated {{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|qid=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}} as a structure well showing features of the mid-{{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|qid=Q334845|lt=Muromachi period|1=Muromachi period}}.

=== Cultural properties ===
<small>(Type and designation date in parentheses)</small>

===Important Cultural Property (national)===
*Honden with 1 ridge tag (architecture; February 8, Meiji 45 ({{ill|lt=1912|Q2077|qid=Q2077|1=1912}}))

=== Access ===
*From {{ill|lt=Toyooka Station (Hyōgo)|Q871612|qid=Q871612|lt=Toyooka Station|1=Toyooka Station (Hyōgo)}} on JR {{ill|lt=San'in Main Line|Q1135170|qid=Q1135170|1=San'in Main Line}}, take {{ill|lt=Zentan Bus|Q11389110|qid=Q11389110|1=Zentan Bus}} to Okuno and get off at "Nakashima Jinja" stop, or take bus to {{ill|lt=Izushi|Q11395756|qid=Q11395756|1=Izushi}} via Kami and walk 15 minutes from "Morio-guchi" stop.

